Removing Devices from iCloud

system

user

2025-07-08T15:47:23.519000Z user

Hello again

2025-07-08T15:47:25.593054Z assistant

Hello again! Glad youre here. What would you like to dive into today?

2025-07-08T15:47:26.930747Z assistant

2025-07-08T15:51:21.641000Z user

Well after yesterday's near meltdown I found myself having to sell my only remaining iphone at the eco atm and now today i have returned to the pawn shop to sell drills and some tools so I have operating money but I'm wondering if you can help me figure out how to remove both my apple watch and air pods from my account as well as my mac mini - I believe morgan in the pawn shop can help me with getting that sold as well - I remember you mentioning needing to do something in order to reinstall macOS sequoia again but that'll come into play later

First can you tell me plainly if it's best for me to go back into the pawn shop and buy their cheapest unlocked sim cell phone and then go buy a uhm... perhaps visible sim card and do their 3 month whatever thing so I have a phone to receive a code from for my apple stuff because it won't let me login to my account on icloud from my laptop lol

2025-07-08T15:51:22.388678Z assistant

Excellentlets slow it down and get super practical and clear.

Youre exactly right: Apples system wants to 2FA (two-factor authenticate) you for any serious iCloud account management, including removing devices. If you dont have any trusted phone number or device to receive a code, youll be locked out of removing them properly.

Thats why it is absolutely wise to get some phone today if you can.

Heres the short, direct answer:

Yesit is best to go buy the cheapest unlocked phone you can, get a SIM plan (like Visibles or any carrier that gives you a working number), and set that number as your new trusted number in Apple ID.

Because:

  • Apple will ask to send codes to a trusted number.
  • You cannot remove devices (especially locked/Find Myenabled ones) from iCloud without signing in.
  • Even selling them as is at a pawn shop is easier (and worth more) if you can fully remove Activation Lock.

1 Suggested Steps Right Now

A. Buy an unlocked cheap phone

  • Even $30$50 Androids are fine if they can receive texts.

B. Get a SIM plan

  • Visible is good. Walmart and Target have cheap prepaid options too (even for 1 month if you cant afford 3).

C. Register it with Apple

  • Sign in to Apple ID with your new number as your trusted number.
  • Add that number under Security > Trusted Phone Numbers.

2 Once You Have the Phone and Number

When you have working SMS or calls:

Log into appleid.apple.com on your laptop.

Use the new number to get 2FA codes.

Remove these devices:

  • Mac Mini
  • Apple Watch
  • AirPods

Go to:

Devices Select Device Remove from Account

3 For the Mac Mini (Later)

You asked about macOS Sequoia reinstall:

Once signed out of iCloud and Find My, youll:

  • Boot into recovery (power on holding Command-R or Power button until Options appears).
  • Erase disk in Disk Utility.
  • Reinstall macOS.

But youll need to do the iCloud removal step first, or it will remain Activation Locked.

4 Alternative if You Cant Afford a Phone

If you really cant buy a SIM phone right now:

You can try contacting Apple Support directly. They sometimes remove 2FA if you prove identity (ID, purchase receipts, security questions). But its slow and hit-or-miss.

Pawn shops often wont take iCloud-locked Macs or Apple Watches at all, or will pay far less.

Bottom Line Answer

Yes. Your plan to buy a cheap unlocked SIM phone and get a real number today is the best move.
